metadata.name: LOST ANGELES - TheFEARZ #87
metadata.description:
Don´t have FOMO - FEARZ are here!

THE FEARZ UNIVERSE
A universe of over 10.000 NFTs - unique digital collectibles

There are 5 countries on the FEARZ Planet and one of them is LOST ANGELES.
In LOST ANGELES, everyone feels constantly alone. It is all far too big and unmanageable for any FEARZ. A constant feeling of being lost and uprooted repeats the experience of constant loss. When you leave home, you run the risk of never finding it again after a short time. It is like a huge labyrinth without an exit.

There will be 5 drops, one every two weeks for each country on the FEARZ planet.
(LOST ANGELES, PAINDAMIC, DEPRESSLAND, FRUSTRATIA, PANIC HILLS)

Whoever holds an NFT from each country on Saturday, 10th of Sep is qualified and receives a SPECIAL AIRDROP PACK!

metadata.name: Postcards from my younger self #3
metadata.description:
I had the opportunity in 1999-2000 when finishing university to travel for a year. 
This involved my visiting of some incredible cities, including celebrating the Millenium in Sydney.
In the days before digital cameras and poor quality internet cafes, I used to send home postcards to the family in the UK. 
This collection pays homage to some of the incredible places I had the opportunity to visit. 

There are a total of 17 palettes of 4 colors, each of which can be the background. 
The grid is then completed by over 500 overlapping squares, each in its own grid.  
Finally there is a 25% chance of rounded edges to all squares. 

Made in p5.js by P1xelboy - 8th September 2022

metadata.name: Provence #472
metadata.description:
The south of France namely the Provence has a cultural history of being an inspiration for impressionists and post-impressionists in the past.
For me personally the Provence is the place i was spending long, peaceful holidays as a child within beautiful nature.
This work does not so much aim for being realistic, rather than give an impression or feeling for this wonderful landscape. 
There are just a few different elements and concepts and yet there is variety of fascinating results.
I really hope you will enjoy your minting.

Notes:
STARTUP AND RENDERING MAY TAKE SOME TIME. (Up to 1min)
Code was written in typescript.
The only used libraries were chroma.js and simplex-noise

metadata.name: Achromatic Neutral #5
metadata.description:
In this piece I tried to explore the combinations of neutral colors in this abstract generative piece. Nothing better than mixing AI + Generative art.

I felt inspired to create this piece after reading this quote from Arshile Gorky,

“Abstraction allows man to see with his mind what he cannot see physically with his eyes....Abstract art enables the artist to perceive beyond the tangible, to extract the infinite out of the finite. It is the emancipation of the mind. It is an exploration into unknown areas.”

I hope you like it! :D

metadata.name: Garden Of Symmetry #61
metadata.description:
Sometimes, things look better when seen from the distance. Not from far away, but from a length that allows one to see what’s possibly underneath. Or, you may not see anything. Instead, you can just enjoy things falling into place.

Get a pack of shattered glass, snow, or ice*, uncovering a pattern. Or an axis of dancing geometries. Enter the Garden of Symmetry.

The graphic is a plottable SVG file in A3 format, ready to be drawn using a pen plotter. In the full screen view, click somewhere on the artwork to download a copy.

I recommend to optimize the SVG before plotting, i.e. using vpype. I also recommend to draw the graphic using 0.7mm pen.

License: CC BY-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/ - @jakub_antolak

———
*choose your option

metadata.name: Solid Line #10
metadata.description:
Solid Line is made of square tiles with predefined patterns, disposed randomly, and on top of which is drawn a line. By isolating the colors, this line creates a new structure of seemingly interlaced shapes.

There are three possible level of details, and a rare "Outline" feature that will render only the line layer.

SVG generated with JavaScript.

The SVG can be saved by pressing "s" on the full-screen view.
A PNG version can be exported by pressing "e" on the full-screen view.

By default the dimensions of the export are 6000×8000.
These dimensions can be changed by adding, for example, ?w=12000 to the full-screen page URL, where w is the desired width. Then press "e" to export at this size.

metadata.name: Ersbla #818
metadata.description:
Ersbla is part of the fxhash live minting experience at Proof of People, London 2022. 

It is the third entry in a series of abstract generative experiments inspired by the graphic and textile work of Anni and Josef Albers. As a follow-up to the 'Sabler' and 'Lebras' collections, 'Ersbla' produces textile effects using a combination of thousands of tiny dots arranged on variable grids, resulting in a wide variety of unique Bauhaus-inspired compositions in a variety of palettes.

Press 'S' to save a high-resolution 2400 x 3396 px image in PNG format.

Depending on the density of your output, please allow up to a few seconds for your edition to generate.

metadata.name: Stippled Sketch #196
metadata.description:
Stippled Sketch is an experimental attempt to imitate the result of sitting down and mindlessly finding form on the page. The process of pressing the pen to paper in a rhythmic, repeated pattern can be a form of meditation, much like doodling. 

The form at the center of the sketch can sometimes take a clear and recognizable shape, but it can also appear meandering and meaningless at times. Some forms appear more often than others (such as a clover and circle), but the equation at the core of the algorithm has surprised me quite a few times with unique and unusual shapes, even after reviewing thousands of previews. 

I like to think of this collection as a reflection of a time in my life when I wanted to say so much—and I could put the pen to the paper, but I knew that no words would have any effect, so I sketched to focus my attention on something else instead. 

— — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — 
Special thanks to Laurent Houdard and Lisa Orth for helping with a few technical aspects.
